Day 7 - focused on Operating System Hardening and implementing the Principle of Least Privilege (PoLP).
I transitioned from using a single administrative account to managing granular user permissions and recovering a system from a critical configuration failure.

🛠️ Skills Mastered
User Management: Created and managed restricted Linux users (useradd, passwd).

Sudoers Configuration: Implemented granular permissions using the modular /etc/sudoers.d/ directory.

System Recovery: Performed "emergency surgery" on a corrupted /etc/sudoers file using sed to remove syntax errors and restore administrative functionality.

Secure Automation: Used echo and tee to inject security policies without manual editor intervention (ideal for User Data scripts).

⚠️ Critical Incident & Resolution (detailed breakdown at the bottom)
During the lab, the main sudoers file became corrupted with syntax errors, causing sudo to fail system-wide.

Issue: Improperly saved characters in /etc/ssh/sshd_config caused a paralysis of administrative commands.

Solution: Utilized sed (Stream Editor) to surgically delete corrupted lines by line number, restoring the system to a healthy state without a reboot.

💡 Architectural Key Concept
Defense in Depth: Security isn't just about the AWS Security Group (Firewall). It is about layering security.
While the Security Group controls who can reach the server, Linux permissions control what they can do once they arrive.

Troubleshooting: Resolving Sudoers Corruption
During the configuration process, the /etc/sudoers file was accidentally saved with syntax errors (exit, x, X), which effectively locked out administrative privileges.

The Challenge:
Standard sudo commands failed with: syntax error at line 135. Because visudo (the safe editor) also relies on the sudoers file to validate permissions, I was stuck in a "What now?" loop where the system refused to save or exit cleanly.

The Solution:

Emergency Exit: Forced a quit from the corrupted visudo session using the (x) exit without saving option to regain terminal control.

Non-Interactive Repair: Used the sed (Stream Editor) utility to delete the specific corrupted lines without opening a manual editor:

Bash
sudo sed -i '134,140d' /etc/sudoers
Validation: Verified system health with sudo ls /root to ensure the syntax was clean.

Architectural Pivot: To prevent future corruption, I abandoned direct modification of /etc/sudoers and switched to the Drop-in Directory method (/etc/sudoers.d/).

Key Takeaway: Never edit the "Main Engine" if you can use a "Plugin." Using sudoers.d ensures that a typo in a user policy doesn't paralyze the entire operating system.

