Day 8 - Implementing a Reverse Proxy on AWS EC2

Overview
Today, I transitioned from a basic web server to a Multi-Tier Architecture by configuring Nginx as a Reverse Proxy. I moved away from dynamic IP addresses by implementing an AWS Elastic IP, 
ensuring a persistent entry point for the server.

Key Technical Concepts
Static Networking: Allocated and associated an Elastic IP to prevent IP address changes on instance reboot.

Reverse Proxy Configuration: Configured Nginx to listen on Port 80 and forward traffic to an internal application running on Port 8080.

Package Management: Installed nc (Netcat) via yum to simulate a backend application environment.

Troubleshooting (The "502 Bad Gateway"): * Diagnosed connection issues between the proxy and the backend.

Utilized ss -tulpn to verify port listening status.

Resolved permission issues by adjusting SELinux boolean settings (httpd_can_network_connect).

Challenges faced:

The Backend (The "Hidden App")
I used a simple command (nc or Netcat) to simulate a real-world application like a Python or Node.js server.

The Challenge: I found the tool wasn't there (command not found).

The Fix: I used yum install

The Result: I had a service running "internally" on the server that only Nginx could easily talk to.

Troubleshooting 
The 502 Bad Gateway was encountered when I searched for the IP address.

Is the Door Open? (Security Groups/Firewalls)

Is the Service Running? (Checking ss -tulpn to see if Port 8080 was listening)

Is the Gateway Allowed to talk? (SELinux permissions)

