Day 9: Mastering the Application Load Balancer (ALB) Handshake
Objective: Deploy a fault-tolerant web architecture and resolve complex Port-Mapping challenges between the Load Balancer and backend services.

Key Accomplishments:

Dynamic Scaling: Re-deployed a high-availability fleet using Auto Scaling Groups (ASG) across three Availability Zones (AZs).

Advanced Port Routing: Successfully configured an ALB to listen on standard web traffic (Port 80) and route it to a custom backend application running on Port 8080.

Infrastructure Debugging: Identified and resolved a "Connection Refused" error by aligning Target Group protocols with backend User Data service configurations.

Security Chaining: Refined Security Group rules to allow seamless traffic flow while maintaining a "Least Privilege" security posture.

Technical Stack:

AWS Services: EC2, Application Load Balancer (ALB), Auto Scaling Groups (ASG), VPC (Internet Gateways & Route Tables).

Scripting: Bash (automated Nginx setup and background Netcat service).

Today highlighted the importance of 'The Handshake.' Even with healthy targets, a single port mismatch can break an entire architecture. By reconfiguring the Target Group to bridge the gap between Port 80 and Port 8080, I achieved a seamless, load-balanced user experience without requiring users to specify custom ports in the URL.

