Day 10: Implementing Scalable Shared Storage with Amazon EFS
Objective: To move from "Local Storage" to "Shared Network Storage," allowing multiple EC2 instances to access a single source of truth simultaneously.

Key Accomplishments:

Provisioned Amazon EFS: Created a high-availability Elastic File System across multiple Availability Zones.

Engineered NFS Security: Configured a dedicated Storage Security Group to allow inbound traffic on Port 2049 (NFS) specifically from the web server tier.

Real-time Data Sync: Successfully mounted the EFS volume to two independent EC2 instances using the amazon-efs-utils helper with TLS encryption.

Validated Persistence: Verified that files created on Instance A were instantly available and editable on Instance B, proving a "stateless" architecture.

Technical Stack:

AWS Services: Amazon EFS, EC2, VPC.

Protocols: NFS v4.1, TCP Port 2049.

Linux Tools: mount, df -h, mkdir, amazon-efs-utils.

The "Cloud Architect" Insight:

"By separating compute from storage, I've created an architecture that is resilient to instance failure. If a server is terminated, the data survives in EFS. This is the foundation for scaling web applications that require shared media or configuration files."

